1
00:00:55,621 --> 00:00:57,213
Somebody asked me today...

2
00:00:57,290 --> 00:01:00,726
"Phil, if you could be anywhere,
where would you like to be?"

3
00:01:00,793 --> 00:01:03,557
I said to him,
"Probably right here."

4
00:01:03,629 --> 00:01:06,894
Elko, Nevada.
Our nation's high at 79 today.

5
00:01:06,966 --> 00:01:09,730
In California,
they'll have warm weather tomorrow...

6
00:01:09,802 --> 00:01:12,566
gang wars and some
very overpriced real estate.

7
00:01:12,638 --> 00:01:17,507
Up in the Pacific Northwest,
they'll have some very tall trees.

8
00:01:17,610 --> 00:01:20,511
It will be clear across
the Rockies and the Great Plains.

9
00:01:20,580 --> 00:01:22,548
But look out,
here comes trouble.

10
00:01:24,984 --> 00:01:28,750
Oh, boy!
Front coming our way. Look out.

11
00:01:28,821 --> 00:01:30,914
What will that mean to us
in the Three Rivers area?

12
00:01:30,990 --> 00:01:34,721
One of these big blue things!
This cold, frigid, Arctic air.

13
00:01:34,794 --> 00:01:36,728
This big mass out of the north.

14
00:01:36,796 --> 00:01:40,926
It will meet up with all this moisture
coming out of the Gulf...

15
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:43,525
mix together at high altitudes
and cause some snow.

16
00:01:43,636 --> 00:01:48,938
It won't hit us here in Pittsburgh.
It will push off and hit Altoona.

17
00:01:49,008 --> 00:01:50,566
Close call.

18
00:01:50,676 --> 00:01:52,769
Let's take a look
at the five-day.

19
00:01:52,845 --> 00:01:56,281
Nothing to be too scared about.

20
00:01:56,349 --> 00:02:00,115
Bundle up warm,
but leave your galoshes at home.

21
00:02:00,186 --> 00:02:01,949
I won't be here for the 10:00.

22
00:02:02,021 --> 00:02:05,286
Tomorrow is Groundhog Day,
and I'm going out to Punxsutawney...

23
00:02:05,358 --> 00:02:07,952
for our country's
oldest groundhog festival.

24
00:02:08,027 --> 00:02:11,463
According to the legend,
tomorrow, February 2...

25
00:02:11,497 --> 00:02:15,456
if the groundhog sees his shadow,
we'll have six more weeks of winter.

26
00:02:15,501 --> 00:02:18,129
- Keep your fingers crossed.
- Sounds like a lot of fun.

27
00:02:18,204 --> 00:02:21,970
This is your third year in a row
isn't it?

28
00:02:22,041 --> 00:02:23,474
Four, Nan.

29
00:02:24,710 --> 00:02:26,143
Thanks, Phil.

30
00:02:26,212 --> 00:02:30,808
Up next: Diane Kingman looks
at sex and violence in the movies.

31
00:02:30,883 --> 00:02:32,316
Stay with us.

32
00:02:35,221 --> 00:02:38,349
- We're clear.
- Have fun in Punxsutawney.

33
00:02:39,425 --> 00:02:41,825
For your information, Hairdo...

34
00:02:41,894 --> 00:02:44,488
there is a major network
interested in me.

35
00:02:44,530 --> 00:02:47,624
That would be
the Home Shopping Network.

36
00:02:48,734 --> 00:02:51,828
Thanks, Larry.
Go wait in the van.

37
00:02:51,904 --> 00:02:54,498
That was nice.
"Big trees."

38
00:02:54,540 --> 00:02:58,636
Stop, Henny.
Can you handle the 10:00 or not?

39
00:02:58,744 --> 00:03:02,510
If you don't want to rush back,
I can do the 5:00 tomorrow.

40
00:03:02,548 --> 00:03:06,006
I want to stay an extra second
in Punxsutawney? Please!

41
00:03:06,085 --> 00:03:10,351
Rita thinks it would be great to stay
for some of the other events...

42
00:03:10,423 --> 00:03:12,118
get some incredible footage.

43
00:03:12,191 --> 00:03:14,853
The people and the fun,
the excitement.

44
00:03:14,927 --> 00:03:18,090
You haven't worked with her yet.
She's really nice.

45
00:03:18,164 --> 00:03:20,564
She's gonna be a really good producer.

46
00:03:21,767 --> 00:03:24,235
You guys will have fun.

47
00:03:26,439 --> 00:03:31,103
She's fun, but not my kind of fun.
I will be here for the 5:00. Rita.

48
00:04:32,838 --> 00:04:35,272
Can you keep a secret, Larry?

49
00:04:35,341 --> 00:04:37,775
I'm probably leaving PBH.

50
00:04:37,843 --> 00:04:42,371
So this will be the last time
we do the Groundhog together.

51
00:04:42,448 --> 00:04:45,940
What's wrong
with the Groundhog Festival?

52
00:04:46,018 --> 00:04:51,081
In San Diego, I covered the swallows
returning to Capistrano six years.

53
00:04:51,157 --> 00:04:53,751
Someday somebody will see me
interviewing a groundhog...

54
00:04:53,859 --> 00:04:55,952
and think I don't have a future.

55
00:04:56,028 --> 00:04:58,462
I think it's a nice story.

56
00:04:58,497 --> 00:05:01,295
He comes out,
and he looks around.

57
00:05:01,367 --> 00:05:05,303
He wrinkles up his little nose.
He sees his shadow or he doesn't see it.

58
00:05:05,371 --> 00:05:07,601
It's nice. People like it.

59
00:05:07,673 --> 00:05:10,608
You are new, aren't you?

60
00:05:10,676 --> 00:05:12,735
People like blood sausage too.

61
00:05:12,845 --> 00:05:14,506
People are morons.

62
00:05:14,580 --> 00:05:16,775
Nice attitude.

63
00:05:16,882 --> 00:05:21,319
Look in the mirror and see what you
look like doing that groundhog thing.

64
00:05:21,387 --> 00:05:22,820
For me? Once?

65
00:05:22,888 --> 00:05:26,984
He comes out
and looks at his little shadow.

66
00:05:28,427 --> 00:05:32,193
- Would you like some blood sausage?
- I like blood sausage.

67
00:06:31,457 --> 00:06:33,687
Rita, I can't stay here.

68
00:06:33,759 --> 00:06:37,217
- Prima donna.
- I'll handle it. What's the matter?

69
00:06:37,296 --> 00:06:40,060
I hate this place. I stayed here
two years ago. I was miserable.

70
00:06:40,132 --> 00:06:43,966
- It's a fleabag. I'm not staying here.
- You're not staying here.

71
00:06:44,036 --> 00:06:46,163
I'm not?

72
00:06:46,238 --> 00:06:49,674
Larry's dropping me off. I booked you
in a nice bed-and-breakfast.

73
00:06:51,477 --> 00:06:57,245
Great. I think this is the trait
of a really good producer:

74
00:06:57,316 --> 00:06:59,011
Keep the talent happy.

75
00:06:59,084 --> 00:07:00,676
Anything I can do.

76
00:07:00,753 --> 00:07:03,745
Would you help me
with my pelvic tilt?

77
00:07:05,157 --> 00:07:06,920
Within reason.

78
00:07:06,992 --> 00:07:09,051
Would you like to have dinner
with Larry and me?

79
00:07:09,128 --> 00:07:12,256
No, thank you.
I've seen Larry eat.

80
00:07:14,633 --> 00:07:17,568
Get your sleep.
I'll see you in the morning.

81
00:07:18,504 --> 00:07:20,972
Don't be late.

82
00:07:22,107 --> 00:07:24,735
Did he actually
call himself"the talent"?

83
00:07:52,838 --> 00:07:54,806
Okay, campers, rise and shine.

84
00:07:54,873 --> 00:07:57,774
Don't forget your booties
because it's cold out there today.

85
00:07:57,843 --> 00:08:00,778
It's cold out there every day.
What is this, Miami Beach?

86
00:08:00,846 --> 00:08:06,478
Not hardly. You can expect hazardous
travel later with that blizzard thing.

87
00:08:06,518 --> 00:08:10,147
"That blizzard thing"?
Here's the report.

88
00:08:10,222 --> 00:08:13,783
The National Weather Service
is calling for a big blizzard thing.

89
00:08:13,859 --> 00:08:17,795
They are. But there's another reason
why today is especially exciting.

90
00:08:17,863 --> 00:08:19,626
Especially cold.

91
00:08:19,698 --> 00:08:21,757
The big question
on everybody's lips...

92
00:08:21,834 --> 00:08:25,326
On their chapped lips.

93
00:08:25,404 --> 00:08:28,339
Do you think Phil will come out
and see his shadow?

94
00:08:28,407 --> 00:08:31,171
- Punxsutawney Phil.
- That's right, woodchuck chuckers.

95
00:08:31,243 --> 00:08:33,336
It's Groundhog Day!

96
00:08:33,412 --> 00:08:38,611
- Get up and check that hog!
- Come here, groundhog!

97
00:08:40,552 --> 00:08:42,019
Good morning.

98
00:08:42,087 --> 00:08:44,180
- You off to see the groundhog?
- I am.

99
00:08:44,256 --> 00:08:46,520
Do you think
it will be an early spring?

100
00:08:46,558 --> 00:08:49,356
I'm predicting March 21.

101
00:08:49,428 --> 00:08:51,521
Good guess.

102
00:08:51,563 --> 00:08:54,964
I think that actually is
the first day of spring.

103
00:09:01,740 --> 00:09:04,038
Did you sleep well, Mr. Connors?

104
00:09:04,109 --> 00:09:06,043
I slept alone, Mrs. Lancaster.

105
00:09:07,479 --> 00:09:10,380
- Would you like some coffee?
- Is there any possibility...

106
00:09:10,449 --> 00:09:13,384
of getting an espresso
or a cappuccino this morning?

107
00:09:13,452 --> 00:09:15,852
I really don't know.

108
00:09:15,921 --> 00:09:18,014
How to spell "espresso"
or "cappuccino."

109
00:09:18,123 --> 00:09:19,681
This looks fine.

110
00:09:19,758 --> 00:09:23,216
- I hope you enjoy the festivities.
- I'm sure I will.

111
00:09:23,295 --> 00:09:25,456
There's talk of a blizzard.

112
00:09:25,497 --> 00:09:29,228
We may catch a break
and have that blizzard blow by us.

113
00:09:29,301 --> 00:09:31,701
All this moisture coming up
out of the south...

114
00:09:31,770 --> 00:09:34,238
will probably push on
east of us.

115
00:09:34,306 --> 00:09:37,707
At high altitudes it will crystallize
and give us what we call snow.

116
00:09:37,776 --> 00:09:39,403
Probably will be some accumulation...

117
00:09:39,478 --> 00:09:43,312
but here in Punxsutawney our high
will be about 30 today, teens tonight.

118
00:09:43,382 --> 00:09:47,318
Chance of precipitation
about 20 percent today and tomorrow.

119
00:09:47,386 --> 00:09:50,480
Did you want to talk about the weather
or were you just making chitchat?

120
00:09:51,523 --> 00:09:54,720
- Chitchat.
- See you later.

121
00:09:54,793 --> 00:09:59,025
- Bye.
- Will you be checking out today?

122
00:09:59,131 --> 00:10:02,259
Chance of departure today:
100 percent.

123
00:10:24,723 --> 00:10:27,521
Phil Connors?
I thought that was you!

124
00:10:27,593 --> 00:10:29,925
How you doing?
Thanks for watching.

125
00:10:29,995 --> 00:10:34,659
Don't tell me you don't remember me.
I sure as heck-fire remember you.

126
00:10:35,734 --> 00:10:41,366
- Not a chance.
- Ned Ryerson!

127
00:10:42,374 --> 00:10:43,864
Needlenose Ned.
Ned the Head.

128
00:10:43,942 --> 00:10:46,502
Come on, buddy.
Case Western High.

129
00:10:46,578 --> 00:10:51,606
I did the whistling belly button trick
at the high school talent show. Bing!

130
00:10:51,683 --> 00:10:55,744
Got the shingles real bad senior year,
almost didn't graduate.

131
00:10:55,821 --> 00:10:57,914
Bing again!

132
00:10:57,990 --> 00:11:02,222
I dated your sister Mary Pat
till you told me not to anymore.

133
00:11:09,034 --> 00:11:11,935
Did you turn pro
with that belly button thing or what?

134
00:11:12,004 --> 00:11:14,495
- I sell insurance.
- What a shock.

135
00:11:14,540 --> 00:11:18,237
Do you have life insurance?
You could always use a little more.

136
00:11:18,310 --> 00:11:21,575
Am I right or am I right
or am I right? Right?

137
00:11:21,647 --> 00:11:27,517
I would love to stand here and talk
with you, but I'm not going to.

138
00:11:27,553 --> 00:11:30,818
- See you.
- I'll walk with you.

139
00:11:30,889 --> 00:11:33,824
Whenever I see an opportunity now,
I charge it like a bull.

140
00:11:33,892 --> 00:11:35,985
Ned the Bull, that's me now.

141
00:11:36,061 --> 00:11:39,997
I have friends who live and die
by the actuarial tables.

142
00:11:40,065 --> 00:11:43,000
It's all one big crap shoot.

143
00:11:43,068 --> 00:11:45,366
Have you ever heard
of single premium life?

144
00:11:45,437 --> 00:11:48,201
I think that really could be
the ticket for you.

145
00:11:48,273 --> 00:11:52,676
God!
It is so good to see you!

146
00:11:52,744 --> 00:11:55,679
- What are you doing for dinner?
- Something else.

147
00:11:55,747 --> 00:11:59,205
It's been great seeing you,
Needlehead. Take care.

148
00:12:03,288 --> 00:12:06,849
Watch out for that first step.
It's a doozy!

149
00:12:13,098 --> 00:12:17,034
Strike up the music
The band has begun

150
00:12:17,102 --> 00:12:20,538
The Pennsylvania Polka

151
00:12:20,606 --> 00:12:24,872
Pick out your partner
and join in the fun

152
00:12:28,113 --> 00:12:32,379
It started in Scranton
It's now number one

153
00:12:32,451 --> 00:12:35,284
It's gonna entertain you

154
00:12:36,955 --> 00:12:38,820
Phil, over here!

155
00:12:38,890 --> 00:12:40,551
Where have you been?

156
00:12:40,626 --> 00:12:44,722
It was horrible.
A giant leech got me.

157
00:12:44,796 --> 00:12:47,560
You're missing all the fun.
These people are great.

158
00:12:47,633 --> 00:12:50,727
Some have been partying all night.
They sing until they get too cold...

159
00:12:50,802 --> 00:12:55,739
then they sit by the fire,
get warm and sing some more.

160
00:12:57,509 --> 00:12:59,909
They're hicks, Rita.

161
00:12:59,978 --> 00:13:04,438
Did you sleep okay without me?
You tossed and turned, didn't you?

162
00:13:04,516 --> 00:13:07,349
- You're incredible.
- Who told you?

163
00:13:07,419 --> 00:13:10,582
It's groundhog time.

164
00:13:14,493 --> 00:13:16,222
On me in three.

165
00:13:16,328 --> 00:13:18,159
Two, one.

166
00:13:18,230 --> 00:13:23,930
Once a year, the eyes of the nation turn
to this tiny Pennsylvania hamlet...

167
00:13:24,002 --> 00:13:25,936
to watch a master at work.

168
00:13:26,004 --> 00:13:28,598
The master?
Punxsutawney Phil...

169
00:13:28,674 --> 00:13:32,110
the world's most famous weatherman,
the groundhog...

170
00:13:32,177 --> 00:13:36,477
who, as legend has it, can predict
the coming of an early spring.

171
00:13:36,515 --> 00:13:41,578
The question we have to ask ourselves
today is, "Does Phil feel lucky?"

172
00:13:43,588 --> 00:13:45,112
Then it's the same old schtick.

173
00:13:45,190 --> 00:13:47,954
The guy with the big stick
raps on the door.

174
00:13:48,026 --> 00:13:50,961
They pull the little rat out.
They talk to him.

175
00:13:51,029 --> 00:13:54,362
The rat talks back and then
they tell us what's gonna happen.

176
00:14:00,472 --> 00:14:02,963
Isn't he cute?

177
00:14:04,710 --> 00:14:08,009
You like your guys
with prominent upper teeth?

178
00:14:18,423 --> 00:14:22,519
"This February 2,
at 7:20 and 30 seconds...

179
00:14:22,561 --> 00:14:25,997
Punxsutawney Phil,
the seer of seers...

180
00:14:26,064 --> 00:14:29,124
prognosticator
of prognosticators...

181
00:14:29,201 --> 00:14:32,637
emerged reluctantly,
but alertly...

182
00:14:32,704 --> 00:14:34,899
in Punxsutawney, Pennsylvania...

183
00:14:34,973 --> 00:14:37,840
and stated in Groundhogese...

184
00:14:37,909 --> 00:14:40,207
'I definitely see a shadow."'

185
00:14:43,081 --> 00:14:46,881
Sorry, folks.
Six more weeks of winter.

186
00:14:52,257 --> 00:14:56,353
On me in three. Two, one.

187
00:14:56,461 --> 00:15:00,192
Television really fails to capture
the true excitement...

188
00:15:00,265 --> 00:15:03,530
of a large squirrel
predicting the weather.

189
00:15:03,602 --> 00:15:05,695
I, for one, am very grateful
to have been here.

190
00:15:05,771 --> 00:15:09,832
From Punxsutawney,
this is Phil Connors. So long.

191
00:15:09,908 --> 00:15:12,399
Want to try it again
without the sarcasm?

192
00:15:12,477 --> 00:15:14,707
We got it.
I'm out of here.

193
00:15:15,781 --> 00:15:17,544
Prima donnas.

194
00:15:30,061 --> 00:15:32,859
Boy, take a look at this.

195
00:15:33,932 --> 00:15:37,026
- What is going on?
- I don't know.

196
00:15:37,102 --> 00:15:39,832
Perhaps it's that giant blizzard
we're not supposed to get.

197
00:15:39,905 --> 00:15:41,566
This is impossible.

198
00:15:43,809 --> 00:15:46,937
Nobody honks this horn but me, pal.

199
00:16:07,933 --> 00:16:09,833
Take this rig out of here.

200
00:16:10,902 --> 00:16:12,927
Commander, what's going on?

201
00:16:13,004 --> 00:16:15,063
There's nothing going on.
We're closing the road.

202
00:16:15,140 --> 00:16:18,906
- Big blizzard moving in.
- What blizzard? It's a couple flakes.

203
00:16:18,977 --> 00:16:21,844
Don't you listen to the weather?
We got a major storm here.

204
00:16:21,913 --> 00:16:24,108
I make the weather!

205
00:16:24,182 --> 00:16:26,616
All this moisture coming up
out of the Gulf...

206
00:16:26,685 --> 00:16:29,245
will push off to the east
and hit Altoona.

207
00:16:29,321 --> 00:16:31,949
Pal, you got that moisture
on your head.

208
00:16:32,023 --> 00:16:36,619
You can go back to Punxsutawney
or you can freeze to death.

209
00:16:36,695 --> 00:16:40,131
It's your choice.
What's it gonna be?

210
00:16:42,734 --> 00:16:44,258
I'm thinking.

211
00:16:44,336 --> 00:16:47,999
All the long-distance lines
are down?

212
00:16:49,274 --> 00:16:53,836
What about the satellite?
Is it snowing in space?

213
00:16:53,912 --> 00:16:59,475
Don't you have a line you keep open
for emergencies or for celebrities?

214
00:16:59,584 --> 00:17:03,486
I'm both.
I'm a celebrity in an emergency.

215
00:17:03,588 --> 00:17:06,022
Can you patch me through
on that line, please?

216
00:17:12,998 --> 00:17:15,023
Can I have one more
with booze in it?

217
00:17:17,269 --> 00:17:18,861
I like it here.

218
00:17:18,937 --> 00:17:22,703
Phil, are you going
to the groundhog dinner?

219
00:17:22,774 --> 00:17:25,538
I had groundhog for lunch.
It wasn't bad.

220
00:17:25,610 --> 00:17:28,170
Tastes like chicken.
You two run along.

221
00:17:30,448 --> 00:17:32,211
Looking foxy tonight, man.

222
00:17:32,284 --> 00:17:35,378
Is your troop selling cookies
again this year?

223
00:17:35,453 --> 00:17:37,819
That's so funny, Phil.

224
00:17:37,889 --> 00:17:39,516
What are you gonna do?

225
00:17:39,591 --> 00:17:43,220
I'm going back to my room
and take a hot shower.

226
00:17:43,295 --> 00:17:46,196
Maybe read Hustler
or something.

227
00:17:46,264 --> 00:17:47,697
Suit yourself.

228
00:17:52,804 --> 00:17:54,237
God!

229
00:18:06,318 --> 00:18:08,912
Yo, Mom.
Isn't there any hot water?

230
00:18:08,987 --> 00:18:11,547
There wouldn't be today.

231
00:18:11,656 --> 00:18:14,420
Of course not.
Silly me.

232
00:18:14,492 --> 00:18:15,925
Sweet dreams.

233
00:18:48,193 --> 00:18:50,787
Nice going, boys.
You're playing yesterday's tape.

234
00:19:09,047 --> 00:19:10,480
Chapped lips.

235
00:19:27,232 --> 00:19:29,291
What the hell?

236
00:19:36,741 --> 00:19:41,178
Good morning.
Off to see the groundhog?

237
00:19:41,246 --> 00:19:43,840
Think it will be an early spring?

238
00:19:43,915 --> 00:19:46,349
Didn't we do this yesterday?

239
00:19:46,418 --> 00:19:48,682
I don't know what you mean.

240
00:19:48,753 --> 00:19:51,017
Don't mess with me, Pork Chop.

241
00:19:51,089 --> 00:19:56,186
- What day is this?
- It's February 2. Groundhog Day.

242
00:19:59,931 --> 00:20:02,024
I thought it was yesterday.

243
00:20:24,289 --> 00:20:26,883
Did you sleep well, Mr. Connors?

244
00:20:26,958 --> 00:20:28,892
Did I sleep well?

245
00:20:28,960 --> 00:20:33,727
- Would you like some coffee?
- Please. I think I'll have a double.

246
00:20:33,798 --> 00:20:36,528
I hope you enjoy the festivities.

247
00:20:36,601 --> 00:20:38,899
There's talk of a blizzard.

248
00:20:41,473 --> 00:20:43,907
Do you ever have deja vu?

249
00:20:43,975 --> 00:20:46,910
I don't think so,
but I could check with the kitchen.

250
00:20:46,978 --> 00:20:48,912
That's okay. Thank you.

251
00:20:50,682 --> 00:20:53,082
Will you be checking out today?

252
00:20:55,153 --> 00:20:59,089
I'd say the chance of departure
is 80 percent.

253
00:21:00,625 --> 00:21:03,116
Seventy-five, eighty.

254
00:21:07,298 --> 00:21:09,357
Excuse me.

255
00:21:09,434 --> 00:21:12,198
Where is everybody going?

256
00:21:12,270 --> 00:21:15,671
To Gobbler's Knob.
It's Groundhog Day.

257
00:21:15,774 --> 00:21:18,436
It's still just once a year,
isn't it?

258
00:21:30,588 --> 00:21:33,955
Phil Connors.
I thought that was you.

259
00:21:36,361 --> 00:21:40,263
Don't you say you don't remember me.
I sure as heck-fire remember you.

260
00:21:41,199 --> 00:21:42,962
Ned Ryerson?

261
00:21:43,034 --> 00:21:46,595
Bing!
First shot right out of the box!

262
00:21:46,671 --> 00:21:49,606
How's it going, old buddy?

263
00:21:49,674 --> 00:21:52,609
Actually, I'm not feeling well.
Would you excuse me?

264
00:21:52,677 --> 00:21:55,145
It's funny
you should mention your health.

265
00:21:55,213 --> 00:21:57,977
You will never guess what I do now.

266
00:21:58,049 --> 00:22:01,143
- Do you sell insurance?
- Bing again!

267
00:22:01,219 --> 00:22:03,278
You are sharp as a tack today.

268
00:22:03,354 --> 00:22:07,984
Do you have life insurance?
If you do, you could always use more.

269
00:22:08,059 --> 00:22:10,152
Right?
Who couldn't?

270
00:22:10,228 --> 00:22:15,791
You know something?
I got a feeling you ain't got any.

271
00:22:15,900 --> 00:22:20,360
- Am I right or am I right?
- I gotta go.

272
00:22:24,709 --> 00:22:28,338
Watch out for that first step.
It's a doozy.

273
00:22:53,571 --> 00:22:55,505
Phil, over here!

274
00:22:57,742 --> 00:23:00,506
- Where have you been?
- Rita, do me a favor.

275
00:23:00,578 --> 00:23:03,877
I need someone to give me
a good hard slap in the face.

276
00:23:05,450 --> 00:23:07,941
- How's that?
- Good.

277
00:23:08,019 --> 00:23:11,887
If you need help with the other cheek,
let me know. I'm right here.

278
00:23:13,458 --> 00:23:16,689
- Something's going on.
- Are you drunk or something?

279
00:23:16,761 --> 00:23:20,390
Drunk's more fun.
Can I be serious for a minute?

280
00:23:20,465 --> 00:23:23,696
- I don't know. Can you?
- I'm being serious.

281
00:23:23,768 --> 00:23:27,829
I'm having a problem.
I may be having a problem.

282
00:23:29,307 --> 00:23:32,834
- It's groundhog time.
- I knew you would say that.

283
00:23:32,944 --> 00:23:36,539
I really feel weird.

284
00:23:36,614 --> 00:23:39,048
Let's just do this,
then we'll talk.

285
00:23:41,152 --> 00:23:42,813
On me in three.

286
00:23:42,921 --> 00:23:44,786
Two, one.

287
00:23:44,856 --> 00:23:48,883
It's Groundhog Day again.

288
00:23:48,993 --> 00:23:53,259
That must mean we're at Gobbler's Knob
waiting for the forecast...

289
00:23:53,331 --> 00:23:55,891
from the world's most famous
groundhog weatherman...

290
00:23:56,000 --> 00:23:57,558
Punxsutawney Phil...

291
00:23:57,635 --> 00:24:01,264
who's just about to tell us
how much more winter we can expect.

292
00:24:07,178 --> 00:24:08,645
This is a riot.

293
00:24:12,116 --> 00:24:13,413
Isn't he cute?

294
00:24:36,908 --> 00:24:39,468
Yeah, Sport,
I know there's a blizzard.

295
00:24:39,510 --> 00:24:42,775
When are the long-distance lines
gonna be repaired?

296
00:24:44,382 --> 00:24:48,318
What if there is no tomorrow?
There wasn't one today.

297
00:24:50,221 --> 00:24:51,620
Hello?

298
00:25:45,743 --> 00:25:48,507
Good morning.
Off to see the groundhog?

299
00:25:54,752 --> 00:25:57,277
Did you sleep well, Mr...

300
00:26:12,303 --> 00:26:13,702
I thought...

301
00:26:15,306 --> 00:26:18,537
Don't say you don't remember me.
I sure as heck-fire remember you.

302
00:26:18,609 --> 00:26:20,873
It's me, Ned Ryerson!

303
00:26:20,945 --> 00:26:23,573
Needlenose Ned. Ned the Head.
Come on, buddy. Case Western...

304
00:26:29,153 --> 00:26:31,383
Over here!

305
00:26:31,456 --> 00:26:34,892
- Where have you been?
- Can we talk about a nonwork matter?

306
00:26:34,959 --> 00:26:37,894
- You never talk about work.
- We really have to talk. Come on.

307
00:26:37,962 --> 00:26:41,261
- It's a creative meeting. Forget it.
- Wait a second. We've got work to do.

308
00:26:41,332 --> 00:26:44,096
I don't.
I've already done it twice.

309
00:26:44,168 --> 00:26:47,103
When you get finished,
meet me in the diner.

310
00:26:49,640 --> 00:26:52,734
- What's that all about?
- I don't know.

311
00:26:52,810 --> 00:26:54,539
Prima donnas.

312
00:26:57,615 --> 00:26:59,048
More coffee, hon?

313
00:26:59,150 --> 00:27:00,913
No, thanks.
Just the check, please.

314
00:27:00,985 --> 00:27:04,751
- These sticky buns are heaven.
- Aren't they?

315
00:27:06,190 --> 00:27:08,750
Just put that anywhere, pal.

316
00:27:08,826 --> 00:27:10,293
Good save.

317
00:27:12,363 --> 00:27:15,423
Tell me why you're too sick to work,
and it better be good.

318
00:27:17,668 --> 00:27:21,764
I'm reliving the same day
over and over.

319
00:27:21,839 --> 00:27:24,774
Groundhog Day. Today.

320
00:27:24,842 --> 00:27:26,776
I'm waiting for the punch line.

321
00:27:26,844 --> 00:27:31,304
Really.
This is the third time.

322
00:27:31,382 --> 00:27:33,373
It's like yesterday never happened.

323
00:27:33,451 --> 00:27:37,547
I am racking my brain, but I can't
imagine why you'd make this up.

324
00:27:37,622 --> 00:27:41,251
I'm not making it up.
I am asking you for help!

325
00:27:41,325 --> 00:27:43,691
What do you want me to do?

326
00:27:43,761 --> 00:27:47,253
I don't know! You're a producer,
come up with something.

327
00:27:47,331 --> 00:27:48,821
You want my advice?

328
00:27:48,900 --> 00:27:53,803
You should get your head examined
if you expect me to believe that story.

329
00:27:53,871 --> 00:27:55,668
Like the groundhog Phil?

330
00:27:59,043 --> 00:28:01,477
Look out for your shadow, pal.

331
00:28:02,346 --> 00:28:04,246
Morons, your bus is leaving.

332
00:28:05,316 --> 00:28:08,080
You guys ready?
We better get going...

333
00:28:08,186 --> 00:28:11,155
- to stay ahead of the weather.
- Let's talk back in Pittsburgh.

334
00:28:11,255 --> 00:28:13,746
I'm not going back to Pittsburgh.

335
00:28:13,824 --> 00:28:16,292
- Why not?
- Because of the blizzard.

336
00:28:16,360 --> 00:28:18,658
You said that would hit Altoona.

337
00:28:18,729 --> 00:28:22,358
I know that's what I said.

338
00:28:22,433 --> 00:28:25,197
I think you need help.

339
00:28:25,269 --> 00:28:28,363
That's what I've been saying.
I need help.

340
00:28:29,907 --> 00:28:32,501
No spots, no clots...

341
00:28:32,577 --> 00:28:35,512
no tumors, no lesions...

342
00:28:35,580 --> 00:28:37,377
no aneurisms.

343
00:28:37,448 --> 00:28:39,382
None that I can see.

344
00:28:39,450 --> 00:28:43,216
If you want a CAT scan or an MRI,
you have to go into Pittsburgh.

345
00:28:43,287 --> 00:28:45,687
I can't go into Pittsburgh.

346
00:28:45,756 --> 00:28:49,021
- Why can't you go into Pittsburgh?
- There's a blizzard.

347
00:28:49,093 --> 00:28:51,027
Right. The blizzard.

348
00:28:51,095 --> 00:28:54,394
You know what you may need,
Mr. Connors?

349
00:28:54,465 --> 00:28:56,399
A biopsy.

350
00:28:56,467 --> 00:28:57,866
A psychiatrist.

351
00:28:59,270 --> 00:29:03,673
That's an unusual problem,
Mr. Connors.

352
00:29:05,476 --> 00:29:08,673
Most of my work is
with couples, families.

353
00:29:08,746 --> 00:29:10,179
I have an alcoholic now.

354
00:29:12,316 --> 00:29:16,719
You went to college, right?
It wasn't veterinary psychology, was it?

355
00:29:16,787 --> 00:29:20,245
Didn't you take some course
that covered this stuff?

356
00:29:20,324 --> 00:29:22,884
Sort of. I guess.

357
00:29:24,328 --> 00:29:26,159
Abnormal psychology.

358
00:29:26,264 --> 00:29:30,963
So, what do I do?

359
00:29:31,035 --> 00:29:33,094
I think we should meet again.

360
00:29:34,171 --> 00:29:36,071
How's tomorrow for you?

361
00:29:38,776 --> 00:29:40,209
Is that not good?

362
00:29:50,988 --> 00:29:53,923
I was in the Virgin Islands once.

363
00:29:53,991 --> 00:29:56,084
I met a girl.

364
00:29:56,160 --> 00:29:59,926
We ate lobster,
drank pina coladas.

365
00:29:59,997 --> 00:30:02,625
At sunset,
we made love like sea otters.

366
00:30:05,836 --> 00:30:08,930
That was a pretty good day.

367
00:30:09,006 --> 00:30:14,672
Why couldn't I get that day
over and over and over?

368
00:30:14,745 --> 00:30:17,612
You know, some guys
would look at this glass...

369
00:30:17,682 --> 00:30:20,617
and they would say,
"That glass is half empty."

370
00:30:20,685 --> 00:30:24,485
Other guys would say,
"That glass is half full."

371
00:30:24,522 --> 00:30:28,117
I peg you as a "glass is half empty"
kind of guy. Am I right?

372
00:30:29,860 --> 00:30:33,626
What would you do
if you were stuck in one place...

373
00:30:33,698 --> 00:30:37,634
and every day was exactly the same,
and nothing that you did mattered?

374
00:30:40,037 --> 00:30:42,972
That sums it up for me.

375
00:30:50,548 --> 00:30:53,346
Good luck.
I'll drop you off.

376
00:30:55,419 --> 00:31:00,254
- This thing sticks. You gotta jiggle it.
- Come on up here.

377
00:31:00,358 --> 00:31:04,522
- My gosh.
- Give me your keys, pal.

378
00:31:04,562 --> 00:31:08,498
Friends don't let friends drive.
Stand up here. Take a deep breath.

379
00:31:08,566 --> 00:31:10,500
You feel okay? Really?

380
00:31:10,568 --> 00:31:12,001
You're all right.

381
00:31:18,576 --> 00:31:21,511
You want to throw up here
or in the car?

382
00:31:21,579 --> 00:31:26,642
- I think both.
- Come on.

383
00:31:35,459 --> 00:31:37,859
I don't think I should be driving.

384
00:31:37,928 --> 00:31:41,193
I don't either.
Watch your head.

385
00:31:41,265 --> 00:31:43,529
Watch your knees.
Don't break anything.

386
00:31:43,601 --> 00:31:46,934
All right.
Let's not forget seat belts.

387
00:31:48,939 --> 00:31:52,033
Who else could go
for some flapjacks right now?

388
00:31:57,047 --> 00:31:59,208
Let me ask you guys a question.

389
00:31:59,283 --> 00:32:03,549
- Shoot.
- What if there were no tomorrow?

390
00:32:03,621 --> 00:32:07,557
No tomorrow? That would mean
there would be no consequences.

391
00:32:07,625 --> 00:32:11,959
There would be no hangovers.
We could do whatever we wanted!

392
00:32:13,130 --> 00:32:17,897
That's true.
We could do whatever we want.

393
00:32:23,507 --> 00:32:27,136
If we wanted to hit mailboxes,
we could let Ralph drive!

394
00:32:33,984 --> 00:32:36,748
- I think they want you to stop.
- Hang on.

395
00:32:42,293 --> 00:32:44,523
It's the same thing
your whole life:

396
00:32:44,595 --> 00:32:47,894
"Clean up your room." " Stand up
straight." " Pick up your feet."

397
00:32:47,965 --> 00:32:52,493
"Take it like a man."
"Be nice to your sister."

398
00:32:52,570 --> 00:32:55,095
"Don't mix beer and wine, ever."

399
00:32:56,674 --> 00:32:59,108
"Don't drive
on the railroad tracks."

400
00:32:59,176 --> 00:33:01,974
Phil, that's one
I happen to agree with.

401
00:33:11,355 --> 00:33:13,789
I don't know, Gus.

402
00:33:13,858 --> 00:33:19,353
Sometimes I think you just have
to take the big chances.

403
00:33:19,430 --> 00:33:21,955
This is the police!
Pull over immediately!

404
00:33:23,234 --> 00:33:25,464
We're talking in here.

405
00:33:30,574 --> 00:33:32,633
I'm betting he'll swerve first.

406
00:33:46,757 --> 00:33:50,158
I'm not gonna live
by their rules anymore.

407
00:33:50,227 --> 00:33:54,721
- I noticed that.
- You make choices and live with them.

408
00:34:08,946 --> 00:34:10,436
My knee.

409
00:34:13,284 --> 00:34:15,218
Let me handle this.

410
00:34:16,787 --> 00:34:20,553
Three cheeseburgers,
two large fries...

411
00:34:20,624 --> 00:34:22,717
two chocolate shakes
and one large Coke.

412
00:34:22,793 --> 00:34:27,025
- And some flapjacks.
- Too early for flapjacks?

413
00:34:42,980 --> 00:34:44,914
Rise and shine, campers!

414
00:34:44,982 --> 00:34:47,746
Don't forget your booties
because it's cold out there today!

415
00:34:47,818 --> 00:34:52,949
It's cold out there every day.
What is this, Miami Beach? Not hardly.

416
00:34:57,328 --> 00:34:59,091
Slept like a baby.
Thank you.

417
00:34:59,163 --> 00:35:01,757
- I'd love some of your coffee.
- I hope...

418
00:35:01,832 --> 00:35:05,598
Flurries moving in later, but
the blizzard will hit outside of town.

419
00:35:05,669 --> 00:35:09,264
Mrs. Lancaster, was anybody
looking for me here this morning?

420
00:35:09,340 --> 00:35:13,572
Perhaps a state official?
Maybe a blue hat, gun, nightstick?

421
00:35:13,677 --> 00:35:16,271
No one like that.
Will there be?

422
00:35:16,347 --> 00:35:17,780
Apparently not.

423
00:35:20,184 --> 00:35:23,278
Hold my room for me, please.
I'm staying an extra day.

424
00:35:29,360 --> 00:35:31,351
Catch you tomorrow, Pops.

425
00:36:10,534 --> 00:36:13,833
I like to see a man of advancing years
throwing caution to the wind.

426
00:36:13,904 --> 00:36:16,998
It's inspiring, in a way.

427
00:36:17,074 --> 00:36:19,599
My years are not advancing
as fast as you might think.

428
00:36:19,710 --> 00:36:21,143
More coffee, hon?

429
00:36:21,211 --> 00:36:22,974
Just keep it coming, please.

430
00:36:23,047 --> 00:36:24,480
Sure thing.

431
00:36:26,250 --> 00:36:28,844
Just put that anywhere, pal.

432
00:36:28,919 --> 00:36:30,352
Good save.

433
00:36:32,423 --> 00:36:36,086
Don't you worry about cholesterol,
lung cancer, love handles?

434
00:36:38,262 --> 00:36:40,093
I don't worry
about anything anymore.

435
00:36:40,164 --> 00:36:42,928
What makes you so special?
Everybody worries about something.

436
00:36:43,000 --> 00:36:47,994
That's exactly what makes me so special.
I don't even have to floss.

437
00:36:57,247 --> 00:36:58,646
What?

438
00:37:00,284 --> 00:37:04,482
"The wretch,
concentered all in self...

439
00:37:04,521 --> 00:37:07,012
Living,
shall forfeit fair renown...

440
00:37:07,091 --> 00:37:10,356
And, doubly dying,
shall go down...

441
00:37:10,427 --> 00:37:13,726
To the vile dust,
from whence he sprung...

442
00:37:13,797 --> 00:37:17,858
Unwept, unhonor'd, and unsung."

443
00:37:17,935 --> 00:37:20,403
Sir Walter Scott.

444
00:37:23,373 --> 00:37:27,241
- You don't like poetry?
- I love poetry.

445
00:37:27,311 --> 00:37:30,747
I just thought that was Willard Scott.
I was confused.

446
00:37:30,814 --> 00:37:33,544
Do you think I'm acting like this
because I'm egocentric?

447
00:37:33,617 --> 00:37:36,916
I know you're egocentric.
It's your defining characteristic.

448
00:37:39,156 --> 00:37:42,717
Are you guys ready? We better get going
to stay ahead of the weather.

449
00:37:42,826 --> 00:37:46,557
Thanks, Larry.
Would you like a doggie bag?

450
00:37:46,630 --> 00:37:50,566
- I'll stay here and finish.
- I thought you hated this town.

451
00:37:50,634 --> 00:37:53,728
It's beginning to grow on me.

452
00:37:53,837 --> 00:37:55,395
Larry, quit staring.

453
00:37:55,472 --> 00:37:57,099
These are excellent.

454
00:38:09,153 --> 00:38:12,452
Did you see the groundhog
this morning?

455
00:38:12,523 --> 00:38:14,957
I never miss it.

456
00:38:15,025 --> 00:38:16,959
What's your name?

457
00:38:18,362 --> 00:38:20,592
Nancy Taylor.
And you are?

458
00:38:20,664 --> 00:38:23,462
- What high school did you go to?
- What?

459
00:38:23,500 --> 00:38:28,130
- High school.
- Lincoln, in Pittsburgh.

460
00:38:28,205 --> 00:38:32,141
- Who are you?
- Who was your senior English teacher?

461
00:38:32,209 --> 00:38:34,473
Are you kidding?

462
00:38:34,511 --> 00:38:38,311
- Your 12th-grade English teacher was...
- Mrs. Walsh.

463
00:38:38,382 --> 00:38:43,149
Nancy. Lincoln. Walsh.
Thanks very much.

464
00:39:04,541 --> 00:39:07,169
Lincoln High School.

465
00:39:07,244 --> 00:39:10,008
I sat next to you
in Mrs. Walsh's English class.

466
00:39:10,080 --> 00:39:12,014
I'm sorry.

467
00:39:15,085 --> 00:39:18,145
- That's amazing.
- You don't remember me, do you?

468
00:39:20,691 --> 00:39:22,386
I even asked you to the prom.

469
00:39:25,529 --> 00:39:28,225
I was short,
and I've sprouted.

470
00:39:31,435 --> 00:39:34,370
Gosh! How are you?

471
00:39:35,239 --> 00:39:38,106
Great.
You look terrific.

472
00:39:38,175 --> 00:39:40,666
You look very terrific.

473
00:39:42,946 --> 00:39:46,507
- I have to do this report.
- Are you a reporter?

474
00:39:46,583 --> 00:39:49,518
I'm a weatherman
with Channel 9 Pittsburgh.

475
00:39:49,586 --> 00:39:51,781
I should have known.
That's great!

476
00:39:51,889 --> 00:39:53,652
Maybe later we could...

477
00:39:53,724 --> 00:39:55,214
Whatever.

478
00:39:55,292 --> 00:39:58,523
Stay right here.
Promise me?

479
00:39:58,595 --> 00:40:01,063
I'll be right back.
Wish me luck.

480
00:40:01,131 --> 00:40:02,530
Good luck!

481
00:40:28,158 --> 00:40:29,716
Who's Rita?

482
00:40:29,793 --> 00:40:31,727
How should I know?

483
00:40:31,795 --> 00:40:34,559
Is this some kind
of one-night stand?

484
00:40:34,631 --> 00:40:37,566
On the contrary, Nancy.
I love you.

485
00:40:37,634 --> 00:40:40,728
